meanings.definition: a fixed limit on the amount of something that someone is allowed to have or is expected to do:
examples: The annual quota of 140,000 green cards is far lower than the demand.
This fiscal year, Congress set a quota of 65,000 visas.
Under the plan, private companies are legally required to fill a 3% quota with young employees.
Many agricultural quotas will be lifted.
production quotas

meanings.definition: a small number of people that accurately represent a larger group in age, sex, race, etc. and are used to find out information about the larger group:
examples: The survey was conducted by MORI among a quota sample of 2,027 respondents aged over 18.

meanings.definition: a method of setting a limit on how much of something a country or company is allowed to have, produce, import, etc.:
examples: The proposed change in the quota system would add millions of barrels of oil to the world market.
The end of the quota system will allow countries to sell as much clothing as they want around the world.

meanings.definition: without any limit on the amount of particular goods that can be imported or exported:
examples: Caribbean nations can export clothing products quota-free and duty-free to the US if they are made from US fabric.

meanings.definition: the quality of being quotable (= suitable for being repeated by someone else):
examples: In terms of quotability, Mark Twain is the American Shakespeare.
His popularity has a lot to do with his quotability.

meanings.definition: Quotable words are suitable for being quoted (= repeated by someone else):
examples: She became a familiar figure, thanks in part to her highly quotable comments on a range of issues.
This film is filled with famous quotable lines.

meanings.definition: A quotable person says a lot of things that are worth quoting (= repeating):
examples: He was eminently quotable and popular with journalists.
She is one of the sport's all-time greatest and most quotable players.

meanings.definition: in a way that is quotable (= suitable for being repeated by someone else):
examples: The play is so quotably funny it would be hard to narrow down my favourite lines to just ten.
His annual press conference generally produced some quotably controversial comments to be discussed afterwards.

meanings.definition: a phrase or short piece of writing taken from a longer work of literature, poetry, etc. or what someone else has said:
examples: At the beginning of the book there's a quotation from Abraham Lincoln.

meanings.definition: the price that a person or company says they will charge to do a piece of work:
examples: We decided to go with the lowest quotation.

meanings.definition: the fact that a company's shares are being traded on a particular stock market:
examples: Changes in the listing rules have reduced the advantage of obtaining a quotation on this stock market.

meanings.definition: a group of words from a book, play, speech, etc., that are repeated by someone who did not write them:
examples: A quotation from Shakespeare prefaces the novel.

meanings.definition: the price that a person says they will charge:
examples: He called back to say the price quotes were "not accurate."

meanings.definition: a statement of how much a job, service, or product will cost:
examples: You can request a quotation for professional indemnity insurance online.
Get at least three quotations for the work.
Written quotations are available on request.

meanings.definition: the price of a company's shares on a stock market at a particular time:
examples: In a few years, trading securities will be digital and people will be able instantly to get stock-price quotations.
By publishing quotations, the market maker raises the profile of the security.

meanings.definition: if a company's shares have a quotation on a particular stock market, they are being traded on it:
examples: A quotation on the London market is a logical next step.
In 2005 the company withdrew its shares from public quotation .

meanings.definition: If you quote a fact or example, you refer to it in order to add emphasis to what you are saying:
examples: Quote me one organization that doesn't have some bad managers.

meanings.definition: to give a price, especially one that will be charged for doing a piece of work:
examples: The architect has quoted £90,000 to build a patio.

meanings.definition: the price that a person or company says they will charge to do a piece of work:
examples: I asked several companies to give me a quote for the building work.

meanings.definition: to repeat words that someone else has said or written:
examples: She quoted him as saying he couldn’t care less.
He illustrated by quoting from Winston Churchill’s speech.

meanings.definition: If you quote a fact or example, you refer to it to provide proof of something:
examples: The judge quoted several cases to support his opinion.

meanings.definition: to state a price or amount that something will cost:
examples: The roofer quoted $3000 to fix the roof.

meanings.definition: to tell a customer how much a job, service, or product will cost:
examples: A law firm in Washington D.C. quoted me a fee of $25,000 to get the paperwork done.
Some insurers will even decline to quote for new business if the home is in a risky area.

meanings.definition: to give the current price of a company's shares or of a currency:
examples: The old system allows market makers to quote prices at which they will buy and sell large blocks of shares through all conditions.
The British pound was quoted at $1.5117, down from $1.5135 in New York.

meanings.definition: to record a company's name on a stock exchange so that its shares can be traded there:
examples: The Footsie is an average of the share prices of the biggest 100 companies quoted on the stock market.

meanings.definition: a statement of how much a job, service, or product will cost:
examples: Most quotes are valid for a month.
If you already have a UK medical policy, ask for a quote for offshore cover.
The quotes for the building work varied from $15,000 to $70,000.

meanings.definition: used to describe a system on a stock market in which prices are given by dealers (= people who buy and sell shares), who change their prices according to demand from investors:
examples: Proponents of quote-driven trading say it creates greater liquidity.
